top.value: 47% of women and girls in Kenya have suffered physical or sexual violence, a figure that rises in times of conflict. At least 900 people were sexually violated in the unrest following Kenya’s 2007 national election. Victims faced stigma, a lack of mental health services, and weak police and justice systems. Many crimes were not reported. Cases that made it to court often failed due to lack of robust evidence. PHR Kenya works to improve the collection and use of forensic evidence to better support victims of sexual crimes. This project will extend their work to improve collection of psychological evidence to support legal cases, and help survivors of sexual violence get mental health care.

About 97% of girls in Guinea are subjected to violence in the form of female genital mutilation (FGM) and about 67% are married off early as children. Some girls die and many suffer health complications or psychological trauma. Child mothers also face high risks of obstetric fistula or maternal death during childbirth, and are denied their education. This project will work holistically in four districts sensitising communities to abandon FGM and child marriage (especially through religious leaders and school clubs), motivating excisors to abandon FGM and law enforcers to implement laws, and referring survivors for support services. It will use lessons learned for advocacy across Africa.

7.2% of Uganda’s population is living with HIV and the rate has been rising since 2006. Stigma continues to marginalize people with HIV and is a key barrier to accessing services. This project will work across five districts in Uganda. It will strengthen and expand the work of two community grassroots organisations that will establish and support a wider network of support groups of people living with HIV. There will be close links with government clinics to improve the quality and availability of HIV services. It will help establish village savings schemes and strengthen opportunities for livelihoods, improving the lives of more than 15,000 people living with HIV.

80 community-based satellite preschools will be set up with communities and local government support across some of the most remote and marginalised areas of Zanzibar and Tanzania. Working closely with local government at all stages, this project will help to create a scalable approach which can be replicated by the government. Teachers will be selected from the community and trained alongside School Management Committees to ensure preschools have the best support. Grants will be offered to communities to develop their preschools (Zanzibar only). Lessons from the project will seek to influence at policy and practice level across both Zanzibar and the mainland.

AbleChildAfrica has been working for 4 years now with a wider remit than the former USDC UK - supporting a range of partners working on innovative solutions to change the lives of disabled children in Africa. Our 2007-2012 strategy has seen us achieving our goal of developing five partnerships accross 3 countries and finding a way to develop a positive approach to partnership with organisations working with disabled children and youth. We are coming to the end of our intial five year strategy and would like this grant to support the development of our next strategic plan consolidating what has been achieved to date and capitalising on our core mission going forward. In addition we would like support in two areas which we think will be key in that strategy - 1. the development of a well considered mechanism through which we can support mainstream development providers working with children to make their programmes and organisations inclusive and 2. the strengthening of our partnership network enabling it to grow and develop cross-network learning which we believe has significant benefits but which is difficult to fund from other sources.

60% of young people in Sierra Leone are unemployed or underemployed. Many had their education disrupted by civil war. Lack of appropriate skills in the labour force slows the country's development. High quality, affordable vocational training in Freetown is not readily available.  The project will train young men and women in life skills and vocational courses matched to employer demand. It will offer business training and mentorship to young entrepreneurs, facilitate work placements and employment through outreach to companies, and raise revenue by charging firms for recruitment and in-house employee training. Of 990 people trained, 514 will secure a job, improve their jobs or establish a business.

Access to safe, adequate and affordable water is a real challenge for people living in slums. Privately-owned boreholes can be an important supply of water but their regulation is not enforced. Recent research has found the quality of water at boreholes in three of Nairobi’s slums to be dangerously poor, containing high levels of harmful bacteria and e-coli. Also that good hygiene practice is uncommon. As a result, local people suffer, and can even die from, diseases such as typhoid fever, diarrhoea and cholera. This project aims to promote safe drinking water and encourage a more sustainable approach to water provision and hygiene. Rather than building new boreholes, the project will make existing boreholes more efficient, cost-effective and safer. Training will be provided so that facilities can be maintained. There will also be hygiene promotion in schools and the community. As a result, people in the slums will be able to source clean water more cheaply and there will be a reduction in water-related diseases contributing to better health and school attendance.

ACE Africa (UK) was registered as a UK Charity in September 2005, following the establishment of local partners ACE Africa (Kenya) in 2003 and later ACE Africa (TZ) in 2007 and exists to provide them with fundraising and technical support aiming to increase organisational autonomy in Africa through institutional strengthening and staff and strategic development. ACE Africa (UK) values effective use of funds keeping UK costs to a minimum, employing one full time Director, an administrator and part time accountant in the UK. ACE Africa (UK) engages two volunteers and employs the Founder (technical support) in Africa. Given its youth and small size in relation to ACE in Africa, ACE Africa (UK) seeks funding for an independent institutional assessment to better enable it to prioritise organisational needs and maximise human and financial resources for the benefit of the entire organisation. Institutional strengthening will support ACE Africa (UK)'s need to increase funding sources for operations in Africa, strengthen governance and staff skills and improve communications, marketing strategies and fundraising opportunities. This in turn will increase opportunities for advocacy and lobbying at the international level supporting the organisational aim of sharing the programming approach with partner organisations in SSA.

300 children with complex disabilities in Central and Eastern Uganda, will benefit from holistic Early Childhood Development (ECD), addressing their health, nutrition, safety, protection, stimulation and care needs. They will also be supported to attend local pre-primary educational settings to prepare them for inclusive primary school.  Evidence collected will help strengthen government policy in Early Childhood Development to increase access and sustain the inclusion of children with complex disabilities who are some of the most marginalised.
